"# Chapter 4 — From switch to gate: relays, tubes, transistors, chips

Chapter 3 gave us the relay. Slow, mechanical, reliable-ish, big. This
chapter walks the arc of how humans replaced the relay four times over
in eighty years, each time by a factor of a thousand or so in speed,
size, and power. Each time by a different physical principle.

The story has a shape you will recognise. **The idea does not change.
Only the substrate.** Boole's algebra runs on relays. Boole's algebra
runs on vacuum tubes. Boole's algebra runs on transistors. Boole's
algebra runs on integrated circuits. Boole's algebra will probably run
on whatever comes after silicon. The idea is portable. The mechanism
is not.

## The vacuum tube, 1904 onward

John Ambrose Fleming, working for the Marconi company in England,
patented the first practical vacuum tube — the diode — in 1904. It was
a glass bulb with a filament and a plate. Heat the filament. Electrons
boil off it. Put a positive voltage on the plate. Electrons stream from
filament to plate. Put a negative voltage on the plate. Nothing flows.
It was a one-way valve for electricity.

Lee de Forest in the United States added a control grid in 1906, making
the **triode.** A tiny voltage on the grid controlled a big current from
filament to plate. Same idea as the relay — small signal controlling
big signal — but electronic, not mechanical. No moving parts. Way faster.
Way more fragile.

A vacuum tube can switch on and off in about a microsecond. A relay
takes about a millisecond. That is a thousand-fold speed-up.

## ENIAC, 1946

The first big American computer built from vacuum tubes was ENIAC, at
the University of Pennsylvania, completed in 1946. About 17,468 vacuum
tubes. It filled a room the size of a school gym. It weighed about 30
tons. It used about 150 kilowatts of power — enough to run a small
factory.

ENIAC could do about 5,000 add operations per second. That was a
thousand times faster than the relay-based Harvard Mark I. It was
extraordinary. It was also unreliable — tubes burned out constantly,
and the operators spent much of their day finding and replacing dead
tubes.

The word **bug** as slang for a software defect comes from Grace Hopper
finding a real moth stuck inside a relay of the Harvard Mark II in
1947. The moth was taped into the logbook with the note *first actual
case of bug being found.* The word predates the story — engineers had
called defects bugs for decades — but the moth is real and it is in the
Smithsonian.

## The transistor, 1947

Bell Labs was the research arm of the American telephone monopoly, and
it was the best-funded industrial research lab in the world at the time.
In late 1947, three physicists there — John Bardeen, Walter Brattain,
and William Shockley — announced a device that did what a vacuum tube
did, but was solid. No filament. No glass envelope. No vacuum. A small
crystal of germanium with three wires poked into it.

They called it the **transistor** — short for transfer resistor. It
switched on and off with a small voltage on one terminal, just like a
tube. It was about the size of a grain of rice. It used almost no power
compared to a tube. It didn't burn out.

Bardeen, Brattain, and Shockley shared the Nobel Prize in Physics in
1956 for the transistor. It is arguably the most consequential
invention of the twentieth century.

A transistor is not literally a switch — it is a **valve.** A small
voltage on the gate (or base) controls how much current flows from the
source (or emitter) to the drain (or collector). At low gate voltage,
no current. At high gate voltage, current flows. You use it as a
switch by only ever putting it in the two extreme states, never in
between.

Here is a stylised ASCII drawing of a transistor:

```
              gate
               |
               |
   source ---+ | +--- drain
             \\|/
              |            (a MOSFET; substrate and body not shown)
              |
             body
```

Put a voltage on the gate. Current flows from source to drain. Ground
the gate. Current stops. Same shape as a relay coil pulling on an
armature, minus the moving parts, plus roughly a factor of a million
in speed.

## Discrete transistors, 1950s

Through the 1950s, computers were built from individual transistors
soldered onto boards. IBM's 7000-series machines used them. Digital
Equipment Corporation's PDP-1, from 1959, used them. These machines
were much smaller than ENIAC — a big cabinet instead of a room — and
much more reliable. But they still needed a lot of transistors, and
soldering thousands of them onto boards was expensive.

The obvious next question: could you make many transistors on the same
piece of material and skip the soldering entirely?

## The integrated circuit, 1958

Two people invented the integrated circuit essentially simultaneously
and independently. Jack Kilby at Texas Instruments built the first
working IC in September 1958 — a phase-shift oscillator on a small
piece of germanium. Robert Noyce at Fairchild Semiconductor filed for
a patent in January 1959 for an integrated circuit made in silicon
with a planar process, which is what everybody actually uses today.

Kilby got the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2000. Noyce died in 1990 and
therefore couldn't share (the Nobel isn't awarded posthumously). Both
of them are correctly named in histories.

The integrated circuit is the game-changer. Instead of soldering
transistors together by hand, you draw a picture of the circuit
photographically, project it onto a silicon wafer coated with
light-sensitive chemicals, and let a chemical process etch the
transistors and wires into the silicon in one step. Suddenly a chip
that used to be a hundred discrete transistors is a single little
package the size of a fingernail.

## Moore's law, 1965

In 1965 Gordon Moore, then working at Fairchild (later a co-founder of
Intel), wrote an article for *Electronics* magazine noting that the
number of transistors on a chip was doubling roughly every one to two
years. He extrapolated. He turned out to be right for about fifty
years.

Moore's law is an **observation, not a physical law.** It has held
because the industry made it hold. Every generation of chip
manufacturing pushed feature sizes smaller — from micrometers in the
1960s, to hundreds of nanometers in the 1990s, to a few nanometers by
the 2020s. Every generation of engineers spent billions of dollars to
make the next generation happen. Moore's law is a **social contract**
between the industry and its customers as much as it is a physics fact.

By the 2020s, feature sizes are so small — a few nanometers — that
you are counting atoms, and quantum effects start to matter, and the
old scaling tricks stop paying off. Moore's law is slowing. But by
now a modern chip has tens of billions of transistors on it. A
smartphone processor has more transistors than there were relays in
every telephone exchange on Earth in 1950 combined.

## The arc, side by side

Let us line up the substrates. Same job — Boolean gate — on four
different technologies:

```
   Technology        Year      Switch time    Size          Power/gate
   ----------        ----      -----------    ----          ----------
   Relay             1830s     ~10 ms         several cm    ~1 W
   Vacuum tube       1906      ~1  us         ~5 cm         ~1 W
   Discrete xtor     1947      ~10 ns         ~5 mm         ~1 mW
   IC transistor     1958      ~1  ns then    micrometer    microwatt
                               <1 ns today    then nm       then nanowatt
```

Four orders of magnitude in speed per generation. Multiple orders in
size. Similar in power. Same three gates every time: AND, OR, NOT.
Same Boolean algebra.

## Speak & Spell — Motoi's north star

Texas Instruments — the same company where Kilby invented the IC — put
out a toy in 1978 called Speak & Spell. It had a small speech-synthesis
chip (the TMS5100), a keyboard, a small display, and a plastic case
with yellow buttons. A child pressed a letter. The toy spoke it. The
child spelled a word. The toy told them whether they got it right.

Speak & Spell used a real integrated circuit. It also used real linear
predictive coding to synthesise speech. It was, honestly, cutting-edge
1978 electronics packaged as a $60 toy.

Motoi's whole design ethos comes from Speak & Spell. **Small. Warm.
Deterministic. The kid feels mastery.** No fancy graphics, no massive
online model, no cloud. A device that does one thing very well and
tells you when you get it right.

That is a chip. That is what you get for the price of one Kilby+Noyce
plus twenty years of Moore's law. A toy that teaches a child to spell.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Substrate doesn't matter to the algebra. Speed and size do matter, and
they are what turn algebra into experience. A Boolean expression
computed on relays is the same expression computed on a modern chip.
The relay took a millisecond. The chip takes a picosecond. That is
the difference between a computer that clicks its way through addition
in an afternoon and a computer that renders a video in real time.

Chapter 5 goes back to Scheme and treats gates as first-class functions.
Then chapters 6 and 7 build actual adders. Then we start caring about
memory (chapter 8). Then it's state machines (chapter 10) and CPUs
(chapter 12). Then we cross the finish line at chapter 16 and Motoi
introduces you to Claude, Gemini, OpenAI, and DeepSeek — the newest
substrate on the shelf.

## The loop appears

Chip manufacturing itself is a loop. Every generation, the same steps
— design, mask, litho, etch, test — get repeated with smaller features.
Moore's law is the outer loop that has run for fifty years. Each pass
of the loop halves the feature size and doubles the density. Same
process, different scale. Same story as the whole book: the shape
persists, the scale changes.

## Next

Chapter 5: we treat gates as Scheme functions and prove NAND alone can
compute everything.
")
